VISUAL ENCODING
Each CVSS Base metric maps to a specific visual property of the glyph.
Outer Ring — Impact on CIA Triad
The ring is divided into three 120° sectors, one per CIA dimension. Each sector's brightness encodes the impact magnitude.
H High impact
L Low impact
N No impact
Top sector: VC Confidentiality
Bottom-right: VI Integrity
Bottom-left: VA Availability
Split Band — Subsequent System Impact
When SC SI SA are non-zero, the ring splits radially: inner band = vulnerable system, outer band = downstream systems.
SC:L, SI:N, SA:N
SC:N, SI:N, SA:N
Split appears only when downstream impact > None
Each band independently shows H / L / N brightness per sector
Segmented Ring — Attack Requirements
AT controls whether the ring is solid or segmented. Segments indicate the exploit requires specific preconditions (e.g., race condition, specific configuration).
P Present
N None
Radial cuts slice through all bands uniformly so inner/outer stay aligned.

AV determines the number of star points. More points = broader network reach.

Star Pointiness — Attack Complexity
AC controls the ratio between star tip and valley radius. Pointy = simple exploit, blunt = complex conditions.
L Low (simple)
Deep sharp points
H High (complex)
Blunt, rounded
Star Outline — Privileges Required
PR controls the star's outline thickness. Thicker border = more barriers to exploitation.
N None
No auth needed
L Low
Basic user
H High
Admin / root
Thin/absent = open, exposed · Thick = shielded, requires privileges
Spikes — User Interaction Required
UI determines spike presence and style. Spikes radiate from star tips outward past the ring.
N None
Self-exploiting, no user action
P Passive
Victim opens file or visits page
A Active
Victim must click / submit / install
Long spikes = auto-exploitable · Bumps = passive trigger · Smooth = deliberate action needed
